Q1 : Future vs CompletableFuture ? 
Ans : 

future  : 
Future<Integer> future = executorService.submit(() -> 10 + 20);
int result = future.get(); // blocks other threads until result is ready
System.out.println(result);

Introduced in Java 5

Used to perform asynchronous tasks

❌ .get() blocks the other thread

❌ No easy way to chain actions or handle exceptions

CompletableFuture : 
CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> 10 + 20)
    .thenApply(result -> result * 2)
    .thenAccept(result -> System.out.println("Final: " + result)); // here we are retriving value through
	// thenAccept() method which does not block any thread

thenAccept() → "I just want to use the result (like printing), I don’t need it anymore."
thenApply() → "I want to process the result and get something back."

Introduced in Java 8

Supports asynchronous programming with non-blocking features

✅ Allows chaining using .thenApply(), .thenAccept()

✅ Supports exception handling (.exceptionally(), .handle())

both are used to handle the tasks asynchronously
  
  
Q2 :  application.yml file and application.properties file if we run both which value it will take
suppose in application.properties i have value = "saurav" and in application.yml i have value : "saurav" 
and if i run the spring boot project which file it will be run application.yml or application.properties 

Ans  : 
If both application.yml and application.properties have the same key, Spring Boot will use the value from 
application.properties. That’s because Spring loads .yml first and then .properties, so the last one wins.
Basically, application.properties overrides .yml if both exist.

or

Spring Boot loads application.yml first 
Then it loads application.properties(this is the latest once)
The last one wins, so application.properties overrides application.yml

Q3 : how we can make win of application.yml file over application.properties
Ans : 
By default, Spring Boot gives priority to application.properties. If you want application.yml to win, don’t put 
the same key in both files. Just define it in application.yml. Or, use a profile like application-dev.yml and 
set spring.profiles.active=dev. This way, Spring will use the value from the .yml file.

Q4 : try with resource ? 
Ans  : 
"try-with-resources is the modern way. It saves time, writes less code, and closes things automatically. 
So it's better than the older try-finally approach." 

so try with resource 
It automatically closes resources like files, streams, DB connections — even if an exception happens.
It's cleaner and avoids bugs like forgetting to close something.

Normal try-finally (old way):

FileReader reader = null;
try {
    reader = new FileReader("data.txt");
    // read file
} finally {
    if (reader != null) {
        reader.close(); // manually closing
    }
}

Try-with-resources (better way):
 
try (FileReader reader = new FileReader("data.txt")) {
    // read file
} // reader is auto-closed here 

